description:
Reproducing is about as easy as could be. Insert data with:
insert into graph <http://test/3807dd61-b064-11e4-8385-7831c1bfeec2> {
  <http://test/3> <http://test/name> "\u00F8"@no.
  <http://test/3> <http://test/age> 3.
}

Now check that it's there:
select * where { graph <http://test/3807dd61-b064-11e4-8385-7831c1bfeec2> {
  ?s ?p ?o
  }
}

Two triples, literal with its nice ø and the language tag. Everything fine.
Then delete both triples:
WITH <http://test/3807dd61-b064-11e4-8385-7831c1bfeec2> DELETE {
  <http://test/3> <http://test/name> "\u00F8"@no.
  <http://test/3> <http://test/age> 3.
}

This reports back that 2 (or less) triples have been deleted, which is perfect. Then verify that they're gone:
select * where { graph <http://test/3807dd61-b064-11e4-8385-7831c1bfeec2> {
  ?s ?p ?o
  }
}

Unfortunately, the "ø"@no is not gone. If you do this whole sequence with just "ø" (without the @no) it works as expected. Makes no difference whether you use SPARQL endpoint over HTTP or if you do this via JDBC (with "SPARQL " in front of all statements).
